# Blade: Laravel component primitives (Acorn)

Applies alongside **`.cursor/rules/05-theme-php-blade-acf.mdc`** (data in composers, `@php` / `@endphp` safety) and **`06-theme-alpine-vite.mdc`** (no inline app JS).

## `$attributes->merge()` in components

Let consumers pass extra classes/attributes. In anonymous or class components:

```blade
<div {{ $attributes->merge(['class' => 'alert alert-'.$type]) }}>
    {{ $message }}
</div>
```

## Prefer components over `@include`

`@include` inherits all parent variables (hidden coupling). **Blade components** expose explicit props, attribute bags, and slots.

## `@pushOnce` for scripts/styles keyed per component

Inside `@foreach`, `@push` runs **N** times. Use **`@pushOnce('scripts', 'component-id')`** ... **`@endPushOnce`** (or the stack name your layout uses) so assets load once.

## `@aware` for deeply nested props

Avoid threading the same prop through every layer; use **`@aware`** for props provided by an ancestor component (Laravel 10+).

## View data

Shared data for views belongs in **View Composers** (`App\View\Composers/*`), **flexible** composers (`Composers/Flexible/*`), or **block** composers (`Composers/Blocks/*` — **`12-acf-blocks.mdc`**) — not duplicated across controllers (Sage has no classic MVC controllers for every view). Same rule as Section N in `05-theme-php-blade-acf.mdc`.

## Fragments (optional)

For **htmx** / **Turbo** partial responses, `->fragmentIf(...)` can return a fragment instead of a full layout — only if the project uses that stack.

## WordPress + Blade

When mixing WP template tags with components, keep **escaping** consistent: Laravel `{{ }}` for simple values; use WordPress **`esc_html_e`**, **`esc_attr`**, etc. where the codebase standard expects them for i18n and WP APIs.

Skill: **`acorn-laravel`** (DI/config); **`tailwindcss-development`** for utility classes in component markup.
